    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix file descriptor leak in VNF P7 socket initialization\n\n### Summary\nDuring VNF initialization, if the P7 socket binding fails or setsockopt operations encounter errors, the opened socket file descriptor is not properly closed, leading to resource leaks. This can cause the VNF to exhaust available file descriptors under repeated failure conditions, eventually preventing new connections.\n\nThe issue occurs in both LTE and NR VNF implementations where socket creation happens but error paths don't ensure proper cleanup. Additionally, memory allocation failures in PNF connection handling could lead to crashes due to NULL pointer dereferences.\n\n### Changes\n- `nfapi/open-nFAPI/vnf/src/vnf_p7_interface.c`: Added `close(vnf_p7->socket)` calls in `nfapi_vnf_p7_start` error paths and NULL check in `nfapi_vnf_p7_add_pnf`\n- `nfapi/oai_integration/socket/socket_vnf.c`: Added `close(vnf_p7->socket)` calls in `nfapi_nr_vnf_p7_start` error paths and NULL check with socket cleanup in `nfapi_nr_vnf_p5_start`\n- `nfapi/oai_integration/nfapi_vnf.c`: Added NULL check in PNF allocation for AERIAL path\n\nTo reproduce: Configure VNF with invalid P7 port binding parameters or force setsockopt failures. Monitor file descriptor usage with `lsof` or `ls -l /proc/<pid>/fd/` - leaked sockets will accumulate over time. Alternatively, trigger memory allocation failures during PNF connection establishment to observe crashes.\n"
}